# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battery-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] An **anode** usually is an electrode of a polarized electrical device through which conventional current enters the device.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] This contrasts with a cathode, which is usually an electrode of the device through which conventional current leaves the device.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] A common mnemonic is ACID, for anode current into device.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The direction of conventional current (the flow of positive charges) in a circuit is opposite to the direction of electron flow, so (negatively charged) electrons flow from the anode of a galvanic cell, into an outside or external circuit connected to the cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] For example, the end of a household battery marked with a *+* is the cathode (while discharging).
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In both a galvanic cell and an electrolytic cell, the anode is the electrode at which the oxidation reaction occurs.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In a galvanic cell, the anode is the wire or plate having excess negative charge as a result of the oxidation reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In an electrolytic cell, the **anode** is the wire or plate upon which excess positive charge is imposed.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] As a result of this, anions will tend to move towards the anode, where they will undergo oxidation.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Historically, the anode of a galvanic cell was also known as the **zincode** because it was usually composed of zinc.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The terms anode and cathode are not defined by the voltage polarity of electrodes, but are usually defined by the direction of current through the electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] An anode usually is the electrode of a device through which conventional current (positive charge) flows into the device from an external circuit, while a cathode usually is the electrode through which conventional current flows out of the device.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In general, if the current through the electrodes reverses direction, as occurs, for example, in a rechargeable battery when it is being charged, the roles of the electrodes as anode and cathode are reversed.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] However, the definition of anode and cathode is different for electrical devices such as diodes and vacuum tubes where the electrode naming is fixed and does not depend on the actual charge flow (current).
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] These devices usually allow substantial current flow in one direction but negligible current in the other direction.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Therefore, the electrodes are named based on the direction of this *forward* current.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In a diode, the anode is the terminal through which current enters and the cathode is the terminal through which current leaves, when the diode is forward biased.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The names of the electrodes do not change in cases where reverse current flows through the device.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Similarly, in a vacuum tube, only one electrode can thermionically emit electrons into the evacuated tube, so electrons can only enter the device from the external circuit through the heated electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Therefore, this electrode is permanently named the cathode, and the electrode through which the electrons exit the tube is named the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Conventional current depends not only on the direction the charge carriers move, but also the carriers' electric charge.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The currents outside the device are usually carried by electrons in a metal conductor.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Since electrons have a negative charge, the direction of electron flow is opposite to the direction of conventional current.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Consequently, electrons leave the device through the anode and enter the device through the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The polarity of voltage on an anode with respect to an associated cathode varies depending on the device type and on its operating mode.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In a discharging battery or galvanic cell (diagram on left), the anode is the negative terminal: it is where conventional current flows into the cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] This inward current is carried externally by electrons moving outwards.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In a recharging battery, or an electrolytic cell, the anode is the positive terminal imposed by an external source of potential difference.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The current through a recharging battery is opposite to the direction of current during discharge; in other words, the electrode that was the cathode during battery discharge becomes the anode while the battery is recharging.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In battery engineering, it is common to designate one electrode of a rechargeable battery the anode and the other the cathode according to the roles the electrodes play when the battery is discharged.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] This is despite the fact that the roles are reversed when the battery is charged.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] When this is done, *anode* simply designates the negative terminal of the battery and *cathode* designates the positive terminal.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In a diode, the anode is the terminal represented by the tail of the arrow symbol (flat side of the triangle), where conventional current flows into the device.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Note the electrode naming for diodes is always based on the direction of the forward current (that of the arrow, in which the current flows *most easily*), even for types such as Zener diodes where the current of interest is the reverse current.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In vacuum tubes or gas-filled tubes, the anode is the terminal where current enters the tube.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The word was coined in 1834 from the Greek ἄνοδος (*anodos*), 'ascent', by William Whewell, who had been consulted by Michael Faraday over some new names needed to complete a paper on the recently discovered process of electrolysis.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The use of *East* to mean the *in* direction (actually *in* → *East* → *sunrise* → *up*) may appear contrived.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Previously, as related in the first reference cited above, Faraday had used the more straightforward term *eisode* (the doorway where the current enters).
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] His motivation for changing it to something meaning *the East electrode* (other candidates had been *eastode*, *oriode* and *anatolode*) was to make it immune to a possible later change in the direction convention for current, whose exact nature was not known at the time.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The reference he used to this effect was the Earth's magnetic field direction, which at that time was believed to be invariant.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] This made the internal current East to West as previously mentioned, but in the event of a later convention change, it would have become West to East, so that the East electrode would not have been the *way in* anymore.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Therefore, *eisode* would have become inappropriate, whereas *anode* meaning *East electrode* would have remained correct with respect to the unchanged direction of the actual phenomenon underlying the current, then unknown but, he thought, unambiguously defined by the magnetic reference.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Since the later discovery of the electron, an easier to remember and more durably correct technically although historically false, etymology has been suggested: anode, from the Greek *anodos*, *way up*, the way (up) out of the cell (or other device) for electrons.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In electrochemistry, the *anode* is where oxidation occurs and is the positive polarity contact in an electrolytic cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] At the anode, anions (negative ions) are forced by the electrical potential to react chemically and give off electrons (oxidation) which then flow up and into the driving circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] This process is widely used in metal refining.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] For example, in copper refining, copper anodes, an intermediate product from the furnaces, are electrolysed in an appropriate solution (such as sulfuric acid) to yield high-purity (99.99%) cathodes.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Copper cathodes produced using this method are also described as electrolytic copper.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Historically, when non-reactive anodes were desired for electrolysis, graphite (called plumbago in Faraday's time) or platinum were chosen.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] They were found to be some of the least reactive materials for anodes.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Platinum erodes very slowly compared to other materials, and graphite crumbles and can produce carbon dioxide in aqueous solutions but otherwise does not participate in the reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In a battery or galvanic cell, the anode is the negative electrode from which electrons flow out towards the external part of the circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Battery manufacturers may regard the negative electrode as the anode, particularly in their technical literature.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Though from an electrochemical viewpoint incorrect, it does resolve the problem of which electrode is the anode in a secondary (or rechargeable) cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Using the traditional definition, the anode switches ends between charge and discharge cycles.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In electronic vacuum devices such as a cathode ray tube, the anode is the positively charged electron collector.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In a tube, the anode is a charged positive plate that collects the electrons emitted by the cathode through electric attraction.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] It also accelerates the flow of these electrons.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In a semiconductor diode, the anode is the P-doped layer, which initially supplies holes to the junction.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In the junction region, the holes supplied by the anode combine with electrons supplied from the N-doped region, creating a depleted zone.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] As the P-doped layer supplies holes to the depleted region, negative dopant ions are left behind in the P-doped layer ('P' for positive charge-carrier ions).
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] This creates a base negative charge on the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] When a positive voltage is applied to the anode of the diode from the circuit, more holes are able to be transferred to the depleted region, and this causes the diode to become conductive, allowing current to flow through the circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The terms anode and cathode should not be applied to a Zener diode, since it allows flow in either direction, depending on the polarity of the applied potential (i.e., voltage).
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In cathodic protection, a metal anode that is more reactive to the corrosive environment than the metal system to be protected is electrically linked to the protected system.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] As a result, the metal anode partially corrodes or dissolves instead of the metal system.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] As an example, an iron or steel ship's hull may be protected by a zinc sacrificial anode, which will dissolve into the seawater and prevent the hull from being corroded.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Sacrificial anodes are particularly needed for systems where a static charge is generated by the action of flowing liquids, such as pipelines and watercraft.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Sacrificial anodes are also generally used in tank-type water heaters.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] In 1824, to reduce the impact of this destructive electrolytic action on ships' hulls, their fastenings and underwater equipment, the scientist-engineer Humphry Davy developed the first and still most widely used marine electrolysis protection system.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Davy installed sacrificial anodes made from a more electrically reactive (less noble) metal attached to the vessel hull and electrically connected to form a cathodic protection circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] A less obvious example of this type of protection is the process of galvanising iron.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] This process coats iron structures (such as fencing) with a coating of zinc metal.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] As long as the zinc remains intact, the iron is protected from the effects of corrosion.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Inevitably, the zinc coating becomes breached, either by cracking or physical damage.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Once this occurs, corrosive elements act as an electrolyte and the zinc/iron combination as electrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The resultant current ensures that the zinc coating is sacrificed but that the base iron does not corrode.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Such a coating can protect an iron structure for a few decades, but once the protective coating is consumed, the iron rapidly corrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] If, conversely, tin is used to coat steel, when a breach of the coating occurs, it actually accelerates oxidation of the iron.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Another cathodic protection is used on the impressed current anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] It is made from titanium and covered with mixed metal oxide.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Unlike the sacrificial anode rod, the impressed current anode does not sacrifice its structure.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] This technology uses an external current provided by a DC source to create the cathodic protection.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] Impressed current anodes are used in larger structures like pipelines, boats, city water tower, water heaters and more.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] When the current through the device is reversed, the electrodes switch functions, so the anode becomes the cathode and the cathode becomes the anode, as long as the reversed current is applied.
[src:battery-chemistry/anode] The exception is diodes, where electrode naming is always based on the forward current direction.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] A **cathode** is the electrode from which a conventional current leaves a polarized electrical device such as a lead–acid battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] This definition can be recalled by using the mnemonic *CCD* for *Cathode Current Departs*.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Conventional current describes the direction in which positive charges move.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Electrons, which are the carriers of current in most electrical systems, have a negative electrical charge, so the movement of electrons is *opposite* to that of the conventional current flow: this means that electrons flow *into* the device's cathode from the external circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] For example, the end of a household battery marked with a + (plus) is the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] The electrode through which conventional current flows the other way, into the device, is termed an anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Conventional current flows from cathode to anode outside the cell or device (with electrons moving in the opposite direction), regardless of the cell or device type and operating mode.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Cathode polarity with respect to the anode can be positive or negative depending on how the device is being operated.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Inside a device or a cell, positively charged cations always move towards the cathode and negatively charged anions move towards the anode, although cathode polarity depends on the device type, and can even vary according to the operating mode.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Whether the cathode is negatively polarized (such as recharging a battery) or positively polarized (such as a battery in use), the cathode will draw electrons into it from outside, as well as attract positively charged cations from inside.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] A battery or galvanic cell in use has a cathode that is the positive terminal since that is where conventional current flows out of the device.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] This outward current is carried internally by positive ions moving from the electrolyte to the positive cathode (chemical energy is responsible for this "uphill" motion).
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] It is continued externally by electrons moving into the battery which constitutes positive current flowing outwards.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] For example, the Daniell galvanic cell's copper electrode is the positive terminal and the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] A battery that is recharging or an electrolytic cell performing electrolysis has its cathode as the negative terminal, from which current exits the device and returns to the external generator as charge enters the battery/ cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] For example, reversing the current direction in a Daniell galvanic cell converts it into an electrolytic cell where the copper electrode is the positive terminal and also the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] In a diode, the cathode is the negative terminal at the pointed end of the arrow symbol, where current flows out of the device.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Note: electrode naming for diodes is always based on the direction of the forward current (that of the arrow, in which the current flows "most easily"), even for types such as Zener diodes or solar cells where the current of interest is the reverse current.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] In vacuum tubes (including cathode ray tubes) it is the negative terminal where electrons enter the device from the external circuit and proceed into the tube's near-vacuum, constituting a positive current flowing out of the device.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] The word was coined in 1834 from the Greek κάθοδος (*kathodos*), 'descent' or 'way down', by William Whewell, who had been consulted by Michael Faraday over some new names needed to complete a paper on the recently discovered process of electrolysis.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] The use of 'West' to mean the 'out' direction (actually 'out' → 'West' → 'sunset' → 'down', i.e.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] 'out of view') may appear unnecessarily contrived.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Previously, as related in the first reference cited above, Faraday had used the more straightforward term "exode" (the doorway where the current exits).
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] His motivation for changing it to something meaning 'the West electrode' (other candidates had been "westode", "occiode" and "dysiode") was to make it immune to a possible later change in the direction convention for current, whose exact nature was not known at the time.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] This made the internal current East to West as previously mentioned, but in the event of a later convention change it would have become West to East, so that the West electrode would not have been the 'way out' any more.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Therefore, "exode" would have become inappropriate, whereas "cathode" meaning 'West electrode' would have remained correct with respect to the unchanged direction of the actual phenomenon underlying the current, then unknown but, he thought, unambiguously defined by the magnetic reference.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Since the later discovery of the electron, an easier to remember, and more durably technically correct (although historically false), etymology has been suggested: cathode, from the Greek *kathodos*, 'way down', 'the way (down) into the cell (or other device) for electrons'.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] In chemistry, a **cathode** is the electrode of an electrochemical cell at which reduction occurs.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] The cathode can be negative like when the cell is electrolytic (where electrical energy provided to the cell is being used for decomposing chemical compounds); or positive as when the cell is galvanic (where chemical reactions are used for generating electrical energy).
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] The **cathodic current**, in electrochemistry, is the flow of electrons from the cathode interface to a species in solution.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] The **anodic current** is the flow of electrons into the anode from a species in solution.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] In an electrolytic cell, the cathode is where the negative polarity is applied to drive the cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Common results of reduction at the cathode are hydrogen gas or pure metal from metal ions.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] When discussing the relative reducing power of two redox agents, the couple for generating the more reducing species is said to be more "cathodic" with respect to the more easily reduced reagent.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] In a galvanic cell, the cathode is where the positive pole is connected to allow the circuit to be completed: as the anode of the galvanic cell gives off electrons, they return from the circuit into the cell through the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] When metal ions are reduced from ionic solution, they form a pure metal surface on the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Items to be plated with pure metal are attached to and become part of the cathode in the electrolytic solution.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] In a vacuum tube or electronic vacuum system, the cathode is usually a metal surface with an oxide coating that much improves electron emission, heated by a filament, which emits free electrons into the evacuated space.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] In some cases the bare filament acts as the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Since the electrons are attracted to the positive nuclei of the metal atoms, they normally stay inside the metal and require energy to leave it; this is called the *work function* of the metal.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] A hot cathode is a cathode that is heated by a filament to produce electrons by thermionic emission.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] The filament is a thin wire of a refractory metal like tungsten heated red-hot by an electric current passing through it.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Before the advent of transistors in the 1960s, virtually all electronic equipment used hot-cathode vacuum tubes.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Today hot cathodes are used in vacuum tubes in radio transmitters and microwave ovens, to produce the electron beams in older cathode ray tube (CRT) type televisions and computer monitors, in x-ray generators, electron microscopes, and fluorescent tubes.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] In order to improve electron emission, cathodes are treated with chemicals, usually compounds of metals with a low work function.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Treated cathodes require less surface area, lower temperatures and less power to supply the same cathode current.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] This is a cathode that is not heated by a filament.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] They may emit electrons by field electron emission, and in gas-filled tubes by secondary emission.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Some examples are electrodes in neon lights, cold-cathode fluorescent lamps (CCFLs) used as backlights in laptops, thyratron tubes, and Crookes tubes.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] They do not necessarily operate at room temperature; in some devices the cathode is heated by the electron current flowing through it to a temperature at which thermionic emission occurs.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] For example, in some fluorescent tubes a momentary high voltage is applied to the electrodes to start the current through the tube; after starting the electrodes are heated enough by the current to keep emitting electrons to sustain the discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Cold cathodes may also emit electrons by photoelectric emission.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] These are often called *photocathodes* and are used in phototubes used in scientific instruments and image intensifier tubes used in night vision goggles.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] In a semiconductor diode, the cathode is the N–doped layer of the p–n junction with a high density of free electrons due to doping, and an equal density of fixed positive charges, which are the dopants that have been thermally ionized.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] In the anode, the converse applies: It features a high density of free "holes" and consequently fixed negative dopants which have captured an electron (hence the origin of the holes).
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] When P and N-doped layers are created adjacent to each other, diffusion ensures that electrons flow from high to low density areas: That is, from the N to the P side.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] They leave behind the fixed positively charged dopants near the junction.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Similarly, holes diffuse from P to N leaving behind fixed negative ionized dopants near the junction.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] These layers of fixed positive and negative charges are collectively known as the depletion layer because they are depleted of free electrons and holes.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] The depletion layer at the junction is at the origin of the diode's rectifying properties.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] This is due to the resulting internal field and corresponding potential barrier which inhibit current flow in reverse applied bias which increases the internal depletion layer field.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Conversely, they allow it in forwards applied bias where the applied bias reduces the built in potential barrier.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Electrons which diffuse from the cathode into the P-doped layer, or anode, become what are termed "minority carriers" and tend to recombine there with the majority carriers, which are holes, on a timescale characteristic of the material which is the p-type minority carrier lifetime.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Similarly, holes diffusing into the N-doped layer become minority carriers and tend to recombine with electrons.
[src:battery-chemistry/cathode] Like a typical diode, there is a fixed anode and cathode in a Zener diode, but it will conduct current in the reverse direction (electrons flow from anode to cathode) if its breakdown voltage or "Zener voltage" is exceeded.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] An **electric battery** is a source of electric power consisting of one or more electrochemical cells with external connections for powering electrical devices.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] When a battery is supplying power, its positive terminal is the cathode and its negative terminal is the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The terminal marked negative is the source of electrons.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] When a battery is connected to an external electric load, those negatively charged electrons flow through the circuit and reach the positive terminal, thus causing a redox reaction by attracting positively charged ions, or cations.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Thus, higher energy reactants are converted to lower energy products, and the free-energy difference is delivered to the external circuit as electrical energy.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Historically the term "battery" specifically referred to a device composed of multiple cells; however, the usage has evolved to include devices composed of a single cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Primary (single-use or "disposable") batteries are used once and discarded, as the electrode materials are irreversibly changed during discharge; a common example is the alkaline battery used for flashlights and a multitude of portable electronic devices.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Secondary (rechargeable) batteries can be discharged and recharged multiple times using an applied electric current; the original composition of the electrodes can be restored by reverse current.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Examples include the lead–acid automotive battery used in internal combustion engine vehicles, and lithium-ion batteries used for portable electronics and electric cars.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Batteries come in many shapes and sizes, from miniature cells used to power hearing aids and wristwatches to, at the largest extreme, huge battery banks the size of rooms that provide standby or emergency power for telephone exchanges and computer data centers.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Batteries have much lower specific energy (energy per unit mass) than common fuels such as gasoline.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In automobiles, this is somewhat offset by the higher efficiency of electric motors in converting electrical energy to mechanical work, compared to combustion engines.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Benjamin Franklin first used the term "battery" in 1749 when he was doing experiments with electricity using a set of linked Leyden jar capacitors.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Franklin grouped a number of the jars into what he described as a "battery", using the military term for weapons functioning together.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] By multiplying the number of holding vessels, a stronger charge could be stored, and more power would be available on discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Italian physicist Alessandro Volta built and described the first electrochemical battery, the voltaic pile, in 1800.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] This was a stack of copper and zinc plates, separated by brine-soaked paper disks, that could produce a steady current for a considerable length of time.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Volta did not understand that the voltage was due to chemical reactions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] He thought that his cells were an inexhaustible source of energy, and that the associated corrosion effects at the electrodes were a mere nuisance, rather than an unavoidable consequence of their operation, as Michael Faraday showed in 1834.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Although early batteries were of great value for experimental purposes, in practice their voltages fluctuated and they could not provide a large current for a sustained period.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The Daniell cell, invented in 1836 by British chemist John Frederic Daniell, was the first practical source of electricity, becoming an industry standard and seeing widespread adoption as a power source for electrical telegraph networks.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] It consisted of a copper pot filled with a copper sulfate solution, in which was immersed an unglazed earthenware container filled with sulfuric acid and a zinc electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] These wet cells used liquid electrolytes, which were prone to leakage and spillage if not handled correctly.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Many used glass jars to hold their components, which made them fragile and potentially dangerous.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] These characteristics made wet cells unsuitable for portable appliances.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Near the end of the nineteenth century, the invention of dry cell batteries, which replaced the liquid electrolyte with a paste, made portable electrical devices practical.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Batteries in vacuum tube devices historically used a wet cell for the "A" battery (to provide power to the filament) and a dry cell for the "B" battery (to provide the plate voltage).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Between 2010 and 2018, battery demand grew by 30% annually, reaching a total of 180 GWh in 2018.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Conservatively, the growth rate is expected to be maintained at an estimated 25%, culminating in demand reaching 2600 GWh in 2030.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In addition, cost reductions are expected to further increase the demand to as much as 3562 GWh.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Important reasons for this high rate of growth of the electric battery industry include the electrification of transport, and large-scale deployment in electricity grids, supported by decarbonization initiatives.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Distributed electric batteries, such as those used in battery electric vehicles (vehicle-to-grid) and in home energy storage with smart metering and that are connected to smart grids for demand response are active participants in smart power supply grids.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Secondary use of partially depleted batteries can add to the overall utility of electric batteries by reducing energy storage costs and emission impact due to longer service life.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In this use, vehicle electric batteries that have their battery capacity reduced to less than 80% (usually after 5–8 years of service) are repurposed for use in backup supplies or renewable energy storage systems.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Grid scale energy storage envisages the large-scale use of batteries to collect and store energy from the grid or a power plant and then discharge that energy at a later time to provide electricity or other grid services when needed.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Grid scale energy storage (either turnkey or distributed) are important components of smart power supply grids.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The advent of computational modeling has revolutionized battery materials design, enabling high-throughput screening and atomistic simulations that accelerate the discovery of novel electrolytes and electrodes, moving beyond traditional trial-and-error approaches.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Batteries convert chemical energy directly to electrical energy.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In many cases, the electrical energy released is the difference in the cohesive or bond energies of the metals, oxides, or molecules undergoing the electrochemical reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] For instance, energy can be stored in Zn or Li, which are high-energy metals because they are not stabilized by d-electron bonding, unlike transition metals.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Batteries are designed so that the energetically favorable redox reaction can occur only when electrons move through the external part of the circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A battery consists of some number of voltaic cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Each cell consists of two half-cells connected in series by a conductive electrolyte containing metal *cations*.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] One half-cell includes electrolyte and the negative electrode, the electrode to which anions (negatively charged ions) migrate; the other half-cell includes electrolyte and the positive electrode, to which cations (positively charged ions) migrate.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Cations are reduced (electrons are added) at the cathode, while metal atoms are oxidized (electrons are removed) at the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Some cells use different electrolytes for each half-cell; then a separator is used to prevent mixing of the electrolytes while allowing ions to flow between half-cells to complete the electrical circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Each half-cell has an electromotive force (*emf*, measured in volts) relative to a standard.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The net emf of the cell is the difference between the emfs of its half-cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Thus, if the electrodes have emfs ${\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ and ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}$ , then the net emf is ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}-{\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ ; in other words, the net emf is the difference between the reduction potentials of the half-reactions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The electrical driving force or $\displaystyle {\Delta V_{\text{bat}}}$ across the terminals of a cell is known as the *terminal voltage (difference)* and is measured in volts.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The terminal voltage of a cell that is neither charging nor discharging is called the open-circuit voltage and equals the emf of the cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Because of internal resistance, the terminal voltage of a cell that is discharging is smaller in magnitude than the open-circuit voltage and the terminal voltage of a cell that is charging exceeds the open-circuit voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] An ideal cell has negligible internal resistance, so it would maintain a constant terminal voltage of ${\mathcal {E}}$ until exhausted, then dropping to zero.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] If such a cell maintained 1.5 volts and produced a charge of one coulomb then on complete discharge it would have performed 1.5 joules of work.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In actual cells, the internal resistance increases under discharge and the open-circuit voltage also decreases under discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] If the voltage and resistance are plotted against time, the resulting graphs typically are a curve; the shape of the curve varies according to the chemistry and internal arrangement employed.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The voltage developed across a cell's terminals depends on the energy release of the chemical reactions of its electrodes and electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Alkaline and zinc–carbon cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.5 volts; likewise NiCd and NiMH cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.2 volts.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The high electrochemical potential changes in the reactions of lithium compounds give lithium cells emfs of 3 volts or more.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Almost any liquid or moist object that has enough ions to be electrically conductive can serve as the electrolyte for a cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] As a novelty or science demonstration, it is possible to insert two electrodes made of different metals into a lemon, potato, etc. and generate small amounts of electricity.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A voltaic pile can be made from two coins (such as a nickel and a penny) and a piece of paper towel dipped in salt water.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Such a pile generates a very low voltage but, when many are stacked in series, they can replace normal batteries for a short time.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Some types of primary batteries used, for example, for telegraph circuits, were restored to operation by replacing the electrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Secondary batteries are not indefinitely rechargeable due to dissipation of the active materials, loss of electrolyte and internal corrosion.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Primary batteries, or primary cells, can produce current immediately on assembly.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] These are most commonly used in portable devices that have low current drain, are used only intermittently, or are used well away from an alternative power source, such as in alarm and communication circuits where other electric power is only intermittently available.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Disposable primary cells cannot be reliably recharged, since the chemical reactions are not easily reversible and active materials may not return to their original forms.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Battery manufacturers recommend against attempting to recharge primary cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In general, these have higher energy densities than rechargeable batteries, but disposable batteries do not fare well under high-drain applications with loads under 75 ohms (75 Ω).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Common types of disposable batteries include zinc–carbon batteries and alkaline batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Secondary batteries, also known as *secondary cells*, or *rechargeable batteries*, must be charged before first use; they are usually assembled with active materials in the discharged state.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Rechargeable batteries are (re)charged by applying electric current, which reverses the chemical reactions that occur during discharge/use.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Devices to supply the appropriate current are called chargers.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The oldest form of rechargeable battery is the lead–acid battery, which are widely used in automotive and boating applications.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] This technology contains liquid electrolyte in an unsealed container, requiring that the battery be kept upright and the area be well ventilated to ensure safe dispersal of the hydrogen gas it produces during overcharging.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The lead–acid battery is relatively heavy for the amount of electrical energy it can supply.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Its low manufacturing cost and its high surge current levels make it common where its capacity (over approximately 10 Ah) is more important than weight and handling issues.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A common application is the modern car battery, which can, in general, deliver a peak current of 450 amperes.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Many types of electrochemical cells have been produced, with varying chemical processes and designs, including galvanic cells, electrolytic cells, fuel cells, flow cells and voltaic piles.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A *wet cell* battery has a liquid electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Other names are *flooded cell*, since the liquid covers all internal parts or *vented cell*, since gases produced during operation can escape to the air.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Wet cells were a precursor to dry cells and are commonly used as a learning tool for electrochemistry.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] They can be built with common laboratory supplies, such as beakers, for demonstrations of how electrochemical cells work.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A particular type of wet cell known as a concentration cell is important in understanding corrosion.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Wet cells may be primary cells (non-rechargeable) or secondary cells (rechargeable).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Originally, all practical primary batteries, such as the Daniell cell, were built as open-top glass jar wet cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Other primary wet cells are the Leclanche cell, Grove cell, Bunsen cell, Chromic acid cell, Clark cell, and Weston cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The Leclanche cell chemistry was adapted to the first dry cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Wet cells are still used in automobile batteries and in industry for standby power for switchgear, telecommunication or large uninterruptible power supplies, but in many places batteries with gel cells have been used instead.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] These applications commonly use lead–acid or nickel–cadmium cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Molten salt batteries are primary or secondary batteries that use a molten salt as electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] They operate at high temperatures and must be well insulated to retain heat.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A *dry cell* uses a paste electrolyte, with only enough moisture to allow current to flow.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Unlike a wet cell, a dry cell can operate in any orientation without spilling, as it contains no free liquid, making it suitable for portable equipment.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] By comparison, the first wet cells were typically fragile glass containers with lead rods hanging from the open top and needed careful handling to avoid spillage.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Lead–acid batteries did not achieve the safety and portability of the dry cell until the development of the gel battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A common dry cell is the zinc–carbon battery, sometimes called the dry Leclanché cell, with a nominal voltage of 1.5 volts, the same as the alkaline battery (since both use the same zinc–manganese dioxide combination).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A standard dry cell comprises a zinc anode, usually in the form of a cylindrical pot, with a carbon cathode in the form of a central rod.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The electrolyte is ammonium chloride in the form of a paste next to the zinc anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The remaining space between the electrolyte and carbon cathode is taken up by a second paste consisting of ammonium chloride and manganese dioxide, the latter acting as a depolariser.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In some designs, the ammonium chloride is replaced by zinc chloride.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A reserve battery can be stored unassembled (unactivated and supplying no power) for a long period (perhaps years).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] When the battery is needed, then it is assembled (e.g., by adding electrolyte); once assembled, the battery is charged and ready to work.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] For example, a battery for an electronic artillery fuze might be activated by the impact of firing a gun.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The acceleration breaks a capsule of electrolyte that activates the battery and powers the fuze's circuits.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Reserve batteries are usually designed for a short service life (seconds or minutes) after long storage (years).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A water-activated battery for oceanographic instruments or military applications becomes activated on immersion in water.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The solid-state battery is also said to have "three times the energy density", increasing its useful life in electric vehicles, for example.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] It should also be more ecologically sound since the technology uses less expensive, earth-friendly materials such as sodium extracted from seawater.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Sony has developed a biological battery that generates electricity from sugar in a way that is similar to the processes observed in living organisms.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The battery generates electricity through the use of enzymes that break down carbohydrates.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The sealed valve regulated lead–acid battery (VRLA battery) is popular in the automotive industry as a replacement for the lead–acid wet cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The VRLA battery uses an immobilized sulfuric acid electrolyte, reducing the chance of leakage and extending shelf life.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] VRLA batteries immobilize the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Other portable rechargeable batteries include several sealed "dry cell" types, that are useful in applications such as mobile phones and laptop computers.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Cells of this type (in order of increasing power density and cost) include nickel–cadmium (NiCd), nickel–zinc (NiZn), nickel–metal hydride (NiMH), and lithium-ion (Li-ion) cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Li-ion has by far the highest share of the dry cell rechargeable market.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] NiMH has replaced NiCd in most applications due to its higher capacity, but NiCd remains in use in power tools, two-way radios, and medical equipment.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Low self-discharge (LSD) allows secondary cells to be charged prior to shipping.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Lithium–sulfur batteries were used on the longest and highest solar-powered flight.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Batteries of all types are manufactured in consumer and industrial grades.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Standard-format batteries are inserted into battery holder in the device that uses them.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] When a device does not uses standard-format batteries, they are typically combined into a custom battery pack which holds multiple batteries in addition to features such as a battery management system and battery isolator which ensure that the batteries within are charged and discharged evenly.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Primary batteries readily available to consumers range from tiny button cells used for electric watches, to the No.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] 6 cell used for signal circuits or other long duration applications.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Secondary cells are made in very large sizes; very large batteries can power a submarine or stabilize an electrical grid and help level out peak loads.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] As of 2017, the world's largest battery was built in South Australia by Tesla.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A battery in Hebei Province, China, which can store 36 MWh of electricity was built in 2013 at a cost of $500 million.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Another large battery, composed of Ni–Cd cells, was in Fairbanks, Alaska.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] It covered 2,000 square metres (22,000 sq ft)—bigger than a football pitch—and weighed 1,300 tonnes.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] It was manufactured by ABB to provide backup power in the event of a blackout.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The battery can provide 40 MW of power for up to seven minutes.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Sodium–sulfur batteries have been used to store wind power.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A 4.4 MWh battery system that can deliver 11 MW for 25 minutes stabilizes the output of the Auwahi wind farm in Hawaii.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Many important cell properties, such as voltage, energy density, flammability, available cell constructions, operating temperature range and shelf life, are dictated by battery chemistry.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A battery's characteristics may vary over load cycle, over charge cycle, and over lifetime due to many factors including internal chemistry, current drain, and temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] At low temperatures, a battery cannot deliver as much power.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] As such, in cold climates, some car owners install battery warmers, which are small electric heating pads that keep the car battery warm.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A battery's *capacity* is the amount of electric charge it can deliver at a voltage that does not drop below the specified terminal voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The more electrode material contained in the cell the greater its capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A small cell has less capacity than a larger cell with the same chemistry, although they develop the same open-circuit voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Capacity is usually stated in ampere-hours (A·h) (mAh for small batteries).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The rated capacity of a battery is usually expressed as the product of 20 hours multiplied by the current that a new battery can consistently supply for 20 hours at 20 °C (68 °F), while remaining above a specified terminal voltage per cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] For example, a battery rated at 100 A·h can deliver 5 A over a 20-hour period at room temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The fraction of the stored charge that a battery can deliver depends on multiple factors, including battery chemistry, the rate at which the charge is delivered (current), the required terminal voltage, the storage period, ambient temperature and other factors.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The higher the discharge rate, the lower the capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] is the capacity when discharged at a rate of 1 amp.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] is the amount of time (in hours) that a battery can sustain.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Charged batteries (rechargeable or disposable) lose charge by internal self-discharge over time although not discharged, due to the presence of generally irreversible *side reactions* that consume charge carriers without producing current.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The rate of self-discharge depends upon battery chemistry and construction, typically from months to years for significant loss.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] When batteries are recharged, additional side reactions reduce capacity for subsequent discharges.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] After enough recharges, in essence all capacity is lost and the battery stops producing power.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Internal energy losses and limitations on the rate that ions pass through the electrolyte cause battery efficiency to vary.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Above a minimum threshold, discharging at a low rate delivers more of the battery's capacity than at a higher rate.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Installing batteries with varying A·h ratings changes operating time, but not device operation unless load limits are exceeded.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] High-drain loads such as digital cameras can reduce total capacity of rechargeable or disposable batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] For example, a battery rated at 2 A·h for a 10- or 20-hour discharge would not sustain a current of 1 A for a full two hours as its stated capacity suggests.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The C-rate is a measure of the rate at which a battery is being charged or discharged.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] It is defined as the current through the battery divided by the theoretical current draw under which the battery would deliver its nominal rated capacity in one hour.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Because of internal resistance loss and the chemical processes inside the cells, a battery rarely delivers nameplate rated capacity in only one hour.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Typically, maximum capacity is found at a low C-rate, and charging or discharging at a higher C-rate reduces the usable life and capacity of a battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Manufacturers often publish datasheets with graphs showing capacity versus C-rate curves.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] C-rate is also used as a rating on batteries to indicate the maximum current that a battery can safely deliver in a circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Standards for rechargeable batteries generally rate the capacity and charge cycles over a 4-hour (0.25C), 8 hour (0.125C) or longer discharge time.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Types intended for special purposes, such as in a computer uninterruptible power supply, may be rated by manufacturers for discharge periods much less than one hour (1C) but may suffer from limited cycle life.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In 2009 experimental lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO 4) battery technology provided the fastest charging and energy delivery, discharging all its energy into a load in 10 to 20 seconds.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In 2024 a prototype battery for electric cars that could charge from 10% to 80% in five minutes was demonstrated, and a Chinese company claimed that car batteries it had introduced charged 10% to 80% in 10.5 minutes—the fastest batteries available—compared to Tesla's 15 minutes to half-charge.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Battery life (or lifetime) has two meanings for rechargeable batteries but only one for non-chargeable batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] It can be used to describe the length of time a device can run on a fully charged battery—this is also unambiguously termed "endurance".
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] For a rechargeable battery it may also be used for the number of charge/discharge cycles possible before the cells fail to operate satisfactorily—this is also termed "lifespan".
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The term *shelf life* is used to describe how long a battery will retain its performance between manufacture and use.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Available capacity of all batteries drops with decreasing temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In contrast to most of today's batteries, the Zamboni pile, invented in 1812, offers a very long service life without refurbishment or recharge, although it can supply very little current (nanoamps).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The Oxford Electric Bell has been ringing almost continuously since 1840 on its original pair of batteries, thought to be Zamboni piles.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Disposable batteries typically lose 8–20% of their original charge per year when stored at room temperature (20–30 °C).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] This is known as the "self-discharge" rate, and is due to non-current-producing "side" chemical reactions that occur within the cell even when no load is applied.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The rate of side reactions is reduced for batteries stored at lower temperatures, although some can be damaged by freezing and storing in a fridge will not meaningfully prolong shelf life and risks damaging condensation.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Old rechargeable batteries self-discharge more rapidly than disposable alkaline batteries, especially nickel-based batteries; a freshly charged nickel cadmium (NiCd) battery loses 10% of its charge in the first 24 hours, and thereafter discharges at a rate of about 10% a month.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] However, newer low self-discharge nickel–metal hydride (NiMH) batteries and modern lithium designs display a lower self-discharge rate (but still higher than for primary batteries).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The active material on the battery plates changes chemical composition on each charge and discharge cycle; active material may be lost due to physical changes of volume, further limiting the number of times the battery can be recharged.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Most nickel-based batteries are partially discharged when purchased, and must be charged before first use.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Newer NiMH batteries are ready to be used when purchased, and have only 15% discharge in a year.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Some deterioration occurs on each charge–discharge cycle.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Degradation usually occurs because electrolyte migrates away from the electrodes or because active material detaches from the electrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Low-capacity NiMH batteries (1,700–2,000 mA·h) can be charged some 1,000 times, whereas high-capacity NiMH batteries (above 2,500 mA·h) last about 500 cycles.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] NiCd batteries tend to be rated for 1,000 cycles before their internal resistance permanently increases beyond usable values.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Fast charging increases component changes, shortening battery lifespan.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] If a charger cannot detect when the battery is fully charged then overcharging is likely, damaging it.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] NiCd cells, if used in a particular repetitive manner, may show a decrease in capacity called "memory effect".
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The effect can be avoided with simple practices.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] NiMH cells, although similar in chemistry, suffer less from memory effect.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Automotive lead–acid rechargeable batteries must endure stress due to vibration, shock, and temperature range.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Because of these stresses and sulfation of their lead plates, few automotive batteries last beyond six years of regular use.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Automotive starting (SLI: *Starting, Lighting, Ignition*) batteries have many thin plates to maximize current.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In general, the thicker the plates the longer the life.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] They are typically discharged only slightly before recharge.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] "Deep-cycle" lead–acid batteries such as those used in electric golf carts have much thicker plates to extend longevity.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The main benefit of the lead–acid battery is its low cost; its main drawbacks are large size and weight for a given capacity and voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Lead–acid batteries should never be discharged to below 20% of their capacity, because internal resistance will cause heat and damage when they are recharged.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Deep-cycle lead–acid systems often use a low-charge warning light or a low-charge power cut-off switch to prevent the type of damage that will shorten the battery's life.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Battery life can be extended by storing the batteries at a low temperature, as in a refrigerator or freezer, which slows the side reactions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Such storage can extend the life of alkaline batteries by about 5%; rechargeable batteries can hold their charge much longer, depending upon type.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] To reach their maximum voltage, batteries must be returned to room temperature; discharging an alkaline battery at 250 mA at 0 °C is only half as efficient as at 20 °C.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Alkaline battery manufacturers such as Duracell do not recommend refrigerating batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] A battery explosion is generally caused by misuse or malfunction, such as attempting to recharge a primary (non-rechargeable) battery, or a short circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] When a battery is recharged at an excessive rate, an explosive gas mixture of hydrogen and oxygen may be produced faster than it can escape from within the battery (e.g. through a built-in vent), leading to pressure build-up and eventual bursting of the battery case.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In extreme cases, battery chemicals may spray violently from the casing and cause injury.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] An expert summary of the problem indicates that this type uses "liquid electrolytes to transport lithium ions between the anode and the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] If a battery cell is charged too quickly, it can cause a short circuit, leading to explosions and fires".
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Car batteries are most likely to explode when a short circuit generates very large currents.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Such batteries produce hydrogen, which is very explosive, when they are overcharged (because of electrolysis of the water in the electrolyte).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] During normal use, the amount of overcharging is usually very small and generates little hydrogen, which dissipates quickly.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] However, when "jump starting" a car, the high current can cause the rapid release of large volumes of hydrogen, which can be ignited explosively by a nearby spark, e.g. when disconnecting a jumper cable.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Overcharging (attempting to charge a battery beyond its electrical capacity) can also lead to a battery explosion, in addition to leakage or irreversible damage.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] It may also cause damage to the charger or device in which the overcharged battery is later used.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Disposing of a battery via incineration may cause an explosion as steam builds up within the sealed case.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Many battery chemicals are corrosive, poisonous or both.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] If leakage occurs, either spontaneously or through accident, the chemicals released may be dangerous.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] For example, disposable batteries often use a zinc "can" both as a reactant and as the container to hold the other reagents.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] If this kind of battery is over-discharged, the reagents can emerge through the cardboard and plastic that form the remainder of the container.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The active chemical leakage can then damage or disable the equipment that the batteries power.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] For this reason, many electronic device manufacturers recommend removing the batteries from devices that will not be used for extended periods of time.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Many types of batteries employ toxic materials such as lead, mercury, and cadmium as an electrode or electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] When each battery reaches end of life it must be disposed of to prevent environmental damage.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Batteries are one form of electronic waste (e-waste).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] E-waste recycling services recover toxic substances, which can then be used for new batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Of the nearly three billion batteries purchased annually in the United States, about 179,000 tons end up in landfills across the country.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Batteries may be harmful or fatal if swallowed.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Small button cells can be swallowed, in particular by young children.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] While in the digestive tract, the battery's electrical discharge may lead to tissue damage; such damage is occasionally serious and can lead to death.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Ingested disk batteries do not usually cause problems unless they become lodged in the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The most common place for disk batteries to become lodged is the esophagus, resulting in clinical sequelae.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Batteries that successfully traverse the esophagus are unlikely to lodge elsewhere.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The likelihood that a disk battery will lodge in the esophagus is a function of the patient's age and the size of the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Older children do not have problems with batteries smaller than 21–23 mm.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Liquefaction necrosis may occur because sodium hydroxide is generated by the current produced by the battery (usually at the anode).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Perforation has occurred as rapidly as 6 hours after ingestion.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Some manufacturers add a bittering agent to their batteries to discourage swallowing.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] Legislation around electric batteries includes such topics as safe disposal and recycling.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In response to reported accidents and failures, occasionally ignition or explosion, recalls of devices using lithium-ion batteries have become more common in recent years.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In the United States, the Mercury-Containing and Rechargeable Battery Management Act of 1996 banned the sale of mercury-containing batteries, enacted uniform labeling requirements for rechargeable batteries and required that rechargeable batteries be easily removable.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] California and New York City prohibit the disposal of rechargeable batteries in solid waste.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The rechargeable battery industry operates nationwide recycling programs in the United States and Canada, with dropoff points at local retailers.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] The Battery Directive of the European Union has similar requirements, in addition to requiring increased recycling of batteries and promoting research on improved battery recycling methods.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] In accordance with this directive all batteries to be sold within the EU must be marked with the "collection symbol" (a crossed-out wheeled bin).
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] This must cover at least 3% of the surface of prismatic batteries and 1.5% of the surface of cylindrical batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/electric-battery] On 9 December 2022, the European Parliament reached an agreement to force, from 2026, manufacturers to design all electrical appliances sold in the EU (and not used predominantly in wet conditions) so that consumers can easily remove and replace batteries themselves.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] An **electrolyte** is a substance that conducts electricity through the movement of ions, but not through the movement of electrons.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] This includes most soluble salts, acids, and bases, dissolved in a polar solvent like water.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Upon dissolving, the substance separates into cations and anions, which disperse uniformly throughout the solvent.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In medicine and sometimes in chemistry, the term electrolyte refers to the substance that is dissolved.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Electrically, such a solution is neutral.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] If an electric potential is applied to such a solution, the cations of the solution are drawn to the electrode that has an abundance of electrons, while the anions are drawn to the electrode that has a deficit of electrons.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] The movement of anions and cations in opposite directions within the solution amounts to a current.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Some gases, such as hydrogen chloride (HCl), under conditions of high temperature or low pressure can also function as electrolytes.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Electrolyte solutions can also result from the dissolution of some biological (e.g., DNA, polypeptides) or synthetic polymers (e.g., polystyrene sulfonate), termed "polyelectrolytes", which contain charged functional groups.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] A substance that dissociates into ions in solution or when molten acquires the capacity to conduct electricity.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Sodium, potassium, chloride, calcium, magnesium, and phosphate in a liquid phase are examples of electrolytes.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In medicine, electrolyte replacement is needed when a person has prolonged vomiting or diarrhea, and as a response to sweating due to strenuous athletic activity.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Commercial electrolyte solutions are available, particularly for sick children (such as oral rehydration solution, Suero Oral, or Pedialyte) and athletes (sports drinks).
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Electrolyte monitoring is important in the treatment of anorexia and bulimia.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In science, electrolytes are one of the main components of electrochemical cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In clinical medicine, mentions of electrolytes usually refer metonymically to the ions, and (especially) to their concentrations (in blood, serum, urine, or other fluids).
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Thus, mentions of electrolyte levels usually refer to the various ion concentrations, not to the fluid volumes.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] The word *electrolyte* derives from Ancient Greek ήλεκτρο- (*ēlectro*-), prefix originally meaning *amber* but in modern contexts related to electricity, and λυτός (*lytos*), meaning "able to be taken apart".
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In his 1884 dissertation, Svante Arrhenius put forth his explanation of solid crystalline salts disassociating into paired charged particles when dissolved, for which he won the 1903 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Arrhenius's explanation was that in forming a solution, the salt dissociates into charged particles, to which Michael Faraday (1791–1867) had given the name "ions" many years earlier.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Faraday's belief had been that ions were produced in the process of electrolysis.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Arrhenius proposed that, even in the absence of an electric current, solutions of salts contained ions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] He thus proposed that chemical reactions in solution were reactions between ions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Shortly after Arrhenius's hypothesis of ions, Franz Hofmeister and Siegmund Lewith found that different ion types displayed different effects on such things as the solubility of proteins.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] A consistent ordering of these different ions on the magnitude of their effect arises consistently in many other systems as well.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] This has since become known as the Hofmeister series.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] While the origins of these effects are not abundantly clear and have been debated throughout the past century, it has been suggested that the charge density of these ions is important and might actually have explanations originating from the work of Charles-Augustin de Coulomb over 200 years ago.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Electrolyte solutions are normally formed when salt is placed into a solvent such as water and the individual components dissociate due to the thermodynamic interactions between solvent and solute molecules, in a process called "solvation".
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] It is also possible for substances to react with water, producing ions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] For example, carbon dioxide gas dissolves in water to produce a solution that contains hydronium, carbonate, and hydrogen carbonate ions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Molten salts can also be electrolytes as, for example, when sodium chloride is molten, the liquid conducts electricity.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In particular, ionic liquids, which are molten salts with melting points below 100 °C, are a type of highly conductive non-aqueous electrolytes and thus have found more and more applications in fuel cells and batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Additionally, highly concentrated electrolytes, or solvent-in-salt electrolytes, are a promising type of electrolyte whereby the concentration of salt exceeds 3 M.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] An electrolyte in a solution may be described as "concentrated" if it has a high concentration of ions, or "dilute" if it has a low concentration.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] If a high proportion of the solute dissociates to form free ions, the electrolyte is strong; if most of the solute does not dissociate, the electrolyte is weak.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] The properties of electrolytes may be exploited using electrolysis to extract constituent elements and compounds contained within the solution.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Alkaline earth metals form hydroxides that are strong electrolytes with limited solubility in water, due to the strong attraction between their constituent ions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] This limits their application to situations where high solubility is required.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In 2021, researchers have found that electrolyte can "substantially facilitate electrochemical corrosion studies in less conductive media".
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In physiology, the primary ions of electrolytes are sodium (Na+), potassium (K+), calcium (Ca2+), magnesium (Mg2+), chloride (Cl−), hydrogen phosphate (HPO42−), and hydrogen carbonate (HCO3−).
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] The electric charge symbols of plus (+) and minus (−) indicate that the substance is ionic in nature and has an imbalanced distribution of electrons, the result of chemical dissociation.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Sodium is the main electrolyte found in extracellular fluid and potassium is the main intracellular electrolyte; both are involved in fluid balance and blood pressure control.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] All known multicellular lifeforms require a subtle and complex **electrolyte balance** between the intracellular and extracellular environments.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In particular, the maintenance of precise osmotic gradients of electrolytes is important.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Such gradients affect and regulate the hydration of the body as well as blood pH, and are critical for nerve and muscle function.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Various mechanisms exist in living species that keep the concentrations of different electrolytes under tight control.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Both muscle tissue and neurons are considered electric tissues of the body.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Muscles and neurons are activated by electrolyte activity between the extracellular fluid or interstitial fluid, and intracellular fluid.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Electrolytes may enter or leave the cell membrane through specialized protein structures embedded in the plasma membrane called "ion channels".
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] For example, muscle contraction is dependent upon the presence of calcium (Ca2+), sodium (Na+), and potassium (K+).
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Without sufficient levels of these key electrolytes, muscle weakness or severe muscle contractions may occur.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Electrolyte balance is maintained by oral, or in emergencies, intravenous (IV) intake of electrolyte-containing substances, and is regulated by hormones, in general with the kidneys flushing out excess levels.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In humans, electrolyte homeostasis is regulated by hormones such as antidiuretic hormones, aldosterone and parathyroid hormones.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Serious electrolyte disturbances, such as dehydration and overhydration, may lead to cardiac and neurological complications and, unless they are rapidly resolved, will result in a medical emergency.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Measurement of electrolytes is a commonly performed diagnostic procedure, performed via blood testing with ion-selective electrodes or urinalysis by medical technologists.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] The interpretation of these values is somewhat meaningless without analysis of the clinical history and is often impossible without parallel measurements of renal function.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] The electrolytes measured most often are sodium and potassium.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Chloride levels are rarely measured except for arterial blood gas interpretations since they are inherently linked to sodium levels.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] One important test conducted on urine is the specific gravity test to determine the occurrence of an electrolyte imbalance.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Conductivity cells are another kind of tools used to measure the electrolyte solution's strength to conduct electricity.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] A home-made electrolyte drink can be made by using water, sugar and salt in precise proportions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] It is important to include glucose (sugar) to utilise the co-transport mechanism of sodium and glucose.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Commercial preparations are also available for both human and veterinary use.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Electrolytes are commonly found in fruit juices, sports drinks, milk, nuts, and many fruits and vegetables (whole or in juice form) (e.g., potatoes, avocados).
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] When electrodes are placed in an electrolyte and a voltage is applied, the electrolyte will conduct electricity.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Lone electrons normally cannot pass through the electrolyte; instead, a chemical reaction occurs at the cathode, providing electrons to the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Another reaction occurs at the anode, consuming electrons from the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] As a result, a negative charge cloud develops in the electrolyte around the cathode, and a positive charge develops around the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] The ions in the electrolyte neutralize these charges, enabling the electrons to keep flowing and the reactions to continue.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] and chlorine gas will be liberated into solution where it reacts with the sodium and hydroxyl ions to produce sodium hypochlorite - household bleach.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] The positively charged sodium ions Na+ will react toward the cathode, neutralizing the negative charge of OH− there, and the negatively charged hydroxide ions OH− will react toward the anode, neutralizing the positive charge of Na+ there.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Without the ions from the electrolyte, the charges around the electrode would slow down continued electron flow; diffusion of H+ and OH− through water to the other electrode takes longer than movement of the much more prevalent salt ions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Electrolytes dissociate in water because water molecules are dipoles and the dipoles orient in an energetically favorable manner to solvate the ions.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In other systems, the electrode reactions can involve the metals of the electrodes as well as the ions of the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Electrolytic conductors are used in electronic devices where the chemical reaction at a metal-electrolyte interface yields useful effects.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Solid electrolytes can be mostly divided into four groups described below.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Gel electrolytes – closely resemble liquid electrolytes.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In essence, they are liquids in a flexible lattice framework.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Various additives are often applied to increase the conductivity of such systems.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Solid ceramic electrolytes – ions migrate through the ceramic phase by means of vacancies or interstitials within the lattice.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] There are also glassy-ceramic electrolytes.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Dry polymer electrolytes differ from liquid and gel electrolytes in that salt is dissolved directly into the solid medium.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Usually it is a relatively high-dielectric constant polymer (PEO, PMMA, PAN, polyphosphazenes, siloxanes, etc.) and a salt with low lattice energy.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In order to increase the mechanical strength and conductivity of such electrolytes, very often composites are made, and inert ceramic phase is introduced.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] There are two major classes of such electrolytes: polymer-in-ceramic, and ceramic-in-polymer.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Organic ionic plastic crystals – are a type organic salts exhibiting mesophases (i.e. a state of matter intermediate between liquid and solid), in which mobile ions are orientationally or rotationally disordered while their centers are located at the ordered sites in the crystal structure.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] They have various forms of disorder due to one or more solid–solid phase transitions below the melting point and have therefore plastic properties and good mechanical flexibility as well as an improved electrode-electrolyte interfacial contact.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] In particular, protic organic ionic plastic crystals (POIPCs), which are solid protic organic salts formed by proton transfer from a Brønsted acid to a Brønsted base and in essence are protic ionic liquids in the molten state, have found to be promising solid-state proton conductors for fuel cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/electrolyte] Examples include 1,2,4-triazolium perfluorobutanesulfonate and imidazolium methanesulfonate.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A **lithium-ion battery** or **Li-ion battery** is a type of rechargeable battery that uses the reversible intercalation of Li+ ions into electronically conducting solids to store energy.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] There are many different varieties, which are usually categorized by the materials used in the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Compared to other types of rechargeable batteries, they generally have higher specific energy, energy density, and energy efficiency and a longer cycle life and calendar life.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In the three decades since Li-ion batteries were first sold in 1991, their volumetric energy density increased threefold while their cost dropped tenfold.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In late 2024, global demand passed 1 terawatt-hour per year, while production capacity was more than twice that.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The invention and commercialization of Li-ion batteries has had a large impact on technology, as recognized by the 2019 Nobel Prize in Chemistry, which was awarded to contributors to the development of Li-ion batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li-ion batteries have enabled portable consumer electronics, laptop computers, cellular phones, and electric cars.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] They are used for grid-scale energy storage and in military and aerospace applications.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li-ion battery sizes are generally not standardised (e.g. in the spirit of the AA battery) and they come in various and unique form factors depending on device and vendor.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] They typically have a nominal voltage of 3.6 or 3.7 V.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Stanley Whittingham conceived intercalation electrodes in the 1970s and created the first rechargeable lithium-ion battery, based on a titanium disulfide cathode and a lithium-aluminium anode, although it suffered from safety problems and was never commercialized.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] John Goodenough expanded on this work in 1980 by using lithium cobalt oxide as a cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The first prototype of the modern Li-ion battery, which uses a carbonaceous anode rather than lithium metal, was developed by Akira Yoshino in 1985 and commercialized by a Sony and Asahi Kasei team led by Yoshio Nishi in 1991.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Whittingham, Goodenough, and Yoshino were awarded the 2019 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their contributions to the development of lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries can be a fire or explosion hazard as they contain flammable electrolytes.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Progress has been made in the development and manufacturing of safer lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion solid-state batteries are being developed to eliminate the flammable electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium and other minerals can have significant issues in mining, with lithium being water intensive in often arid regions and other minerals used in some Li-ion chemistries potentially being conflict minerals such as cobalt.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Environmental issues have encouraged some researchers to improve mineral efficiency and find alternatives such as lithium iron phosphate lithium-ion chemistries or non-lithium-based battery chemistries such as sodium-ion and iron-air batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion cells can be manufactured to optimize energy density or power density.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Handheld electronics mostly use lithium polymer batteries (with a polymer gel as an electrolyte), a lithium cobalt oxide (LiCoO 2) cathode material, and a graphite anode, which together offer high energy density.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO 4), lithium manganese oxide (LiMn 2O 4 spinel, or Li 2MnO 3-based lithium-rich layered materials, LMR-NMC), and lithium nickel manganese cobalt oxide (LiNiMnCoO 2 or NMC) may offer longer life and a higher discharge rate.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] NMC and its derivatives are widely used in the electrification of transport, one of the main technologies (combined with renewable energy) for reducing greenhouse gas emissions from vehicles.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium nickel cobalt aluminum oxide (NCA) is another high-energy lithium-ion chemistry commonly used in electric vehicle batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One of the earliest examples of research into lithium-ion batteries is a CuF 2/Li battery developed by NASA in 1965.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The breakthrough that produced the earliest form of the modern Li-ion battery was made by British chemist M.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Stanley Whittingham in 1974, who first used titanium disulfide (TiS 2) as a cathode material, which has a layered structure that can take in lithium ions without significant changes to its crystal structure.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Exxon tried to commercialize this battery in the late 1970s, but found the synthesis expensive and complex, as TiS 2 is sensitive to moisture and releases toxic hydrogen sulfide (H 2S) gas on contact with water.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] More prohibitively, the batteries were also prone to spontaneously catch fire due to the presence of metallic lithium in the cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] For this, and other reasons, Exxon discontinued the development of Whittingham's lithium-titanium disulfide battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1980, working in separate groups Ned A.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Godshall et al., and, shortly thereafter, Koichi Mizushima and John B.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Goodenough, after testing a range of alternative materials, replaced TiS 2 with lithium cobalt oxide (LiCoO 2, or LCO), which has a similar layered structure but offers a higher voltage and is much more stable in air.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This material would later be used in the first commercial Li-ion battery, although it did not, on its own, resolve the persistent issue of flammability.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] These early attempts to develop rechargeable Li-ion batteries used lithium metal anodes, which were ultimately abandoned due to safety concerns, as lithium metal is unstable and prone to dendrite formation, which can cause short-circuiting.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The eventual solution was to use an intercalation anode, similar to that used for the cathode, which prevents the formation of lithium metal during battery charging.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The first to demonstrate lithium ion reversible intercalation into graphite anodes was Jürgen Otto Besenhard in 1974.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Besenhard used organic solvents such as carbonates, however these solvents decomposed rapidly providing short battery cycle life.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Later, in 1980, Rachid Yazami used a solid organic electrolyte, polyethylene oxide, which was more stable.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1985, Akira Yoshino at Asahi Kasei Corporation discovered that petroleum coke, a less graphitized form of carbon, can reversibly intercalate Li-ions at a low potential of ~0.5 V relative to Li+ /Li without structural degradation.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Its structural stability originates from its amorphous carbon regions, which serve as covalent joints to pin the layers together.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Although it has a lower capacity compared to graphite (~Li0.5C6, 186 mAh g–1), it became the first commercial intercalation anode for Li-ion batteries owing to its cycling stability.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1987, Yoshino patented what would become the first commercial lithium-ion battery using this anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] He used Goodenough's previously reported LiCoO2 as the cathode and a carbonate ester-based electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The battery was assembled in the discharged state, which made it safer and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1991, using Yoshino's design, Sony began producing and selling the world's first rechargeable lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The following year, a joint venture between Toshiba and Asahi Kasei Co. also released a lithium-ion battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Significant improvements in energy density were achieved in the 1990s by replacing Yoshino's soft carbon anode first with hard carbon and later with graphite.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 1990, Jeff Dahn and two colleagues at Dalhousie University (Canada) reported reversible intercalation of lithium ions into graphite in the presence of ethylene carbonate solvent (which is solid at room temperature and is mixed with other solvents to make a liquid).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This represented the final innovation of the era that created the basic design of the modern lithium-ion battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 2010, global lithium-ion battery production capacity was 20 gigawatt-hours.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By 2016, it was 28 GWh, with 16.4 GWh in China.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Global production capacity was 767 GWh in 2020, with China accounting for 75%.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Production in 2021 is estimated by various sources to be between 200 and 600 GWh, and predictions for 2023 range from 400 to 1,100 GWh.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Goodenough, Rachid Yazami and Akira Yoshino received the 2012 IEEE Medal for Environmental and Safety Technologies for developing the lithium-ion battery; Goodenough, Whittingham, and Yoshino were awarded the 2019 Nobel Prize in Chemistry "for the development of lithium-ion batteries".
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Jeff Dahn received the ECS Battery Division Technology Award (2011) and the Yeager award from the International Battery Materials Association (2016).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries are constructed of several key components, including an anode, cathode, separator, casing, electrolyte, and a pair of current collectors.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Typically, the negative electrode of a conventional lithium-ion cell is made from graphite.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The positive electrode is typically a metal oxide or phosphate.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte is a lithium salt in an organic solvent.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The negative electrode (which is the anode when the cell is discharging) and the positive electrode (which is the cathode when discharging) are prevented from shorting by a separator.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrodes are connected to the powered circuit through two pieces of metal called current collectors.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The negative and positive electrodes swap their electrochemical roles (anode and cathode) when the cell is charged.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Despite this, in discussions of battery design the negative electrode of a rechargeable cell is often just called "the anode" and the positive electrode "the cathode".
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In its fully lithiated state of LiC6, graphite correlates to a theoretical capacity of 1339 coulombs per gram (372 mAh/g).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The positive electrode is generally one of three materials: a layered oxide (such as lithium cobalt oxide), a polyanion (such as lithium iron phosphate) or a spinel (such as lithium manganese oxide).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] More experimental materials include graphene-containing electrodes, although these remain far from commercially viable due to their high cost.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium reacts vigorously with water to form lithium hydroxide (LiOH) and hydrogen gas.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Thus, a non-aqueous electrolyte is typically used, and a sealed container rigidly excludes moisture from the battery pack.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The non-aqueous electrolyte is typically a mixture of organic carbonates such as ethylene carbonate and propylene carbonate containing complexes of lithium ions.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Ethylene carbonate is essential for making solid electrolyte interphase on the carbon anode, but since it is solid at room temperature, a liquid solvent (such as propylene carbonate or diethyl carbonate) is added.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte salt is almost always lithium hexafluorophosphate (LiPF 6), which combines good ionic conductivity with chemical and electrochemical stability.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The hexafluorophosphate anion is essential for passivating the aluminium current collector used for the positive electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A titanium tab is ultrasonically welded to the aluminium current collector.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Copper (with a spot-welded nickel tab) is used as the current collector at the negative electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Current collector design and surface treatments may take various forms: foil, mesh, foam (dealloyed), etched (wholly or selectively), and coated (with various materials) to improve electrical characteristics.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Depending on materials choices, the voltage, energy density, life, and safety of a lithium-ion cell can change dramatically.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Current effort has been exploring the use of novel architectures using nanotechnology to improve performance.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Areas of interest include nano-scale electrode materials and alternative electrode structures.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The reactants in the electrochemical reactions in a lithium-ion cell are the materials of the electrodes, both of which are compounds containing lithium atoms.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Although many thousands of different materials have been investigated, only a very small number are commercially usable.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] All commercial Li-ion cells use intercalation compounds as active materials.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The negative electrode is usually graphite, although silicon is often mixed in to increase the capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte is usually lithium hexafluorophosphate, dissolved in a mixture of organic carbonates.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A number of different materials are used for the positive electrode, such as LiCoO2, LiFePO4, and lithium nickel manganese cobalt oxides.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During cell discharge the negative electrode is the anode and the positive electrode the cathode: electrons flow from the anode to the cathode through the external circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] An oxidation half-reaction at the anode produces positively charged lithium ions and negatively charged electrons.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The oxidation half-reaction may also produce uncharged material that remains at the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium ions move through the electrolyte; electrons move through the external circuit toward the cathode where they recombine with the cathode material in a reduction half-reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The electrolyte provides a conductive medium for lithium ions but does not partake in the electrochemical reaction.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The reactions during discharge lower the chemical potential of the cell, so discharging transfers energy from the cell to wherever the electric current dissipates its energy, mostly in the external circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During charging these reactions and transports go in the opposite direction: electrons move from the positive electrode to the negative electrode through the external circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] To charge the cell the external circuit has to provide electrical energy.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This energy is then stored as chemical energy in the cell (with some loss, e. g., due to coulombic efficiency lower than 1).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Both electrodes allow lithium ions to move in and out of their structures with a process called *insertion* (*intercalation*) or *extraction* (*deintercalation*), respectively.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] As the lithium ions "rock" back and forth between the two electrodes, these batteries are also known as "rocking-chair batteries" or "swing batteries" (a term given by some European industries).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The following equations exemplify the chemistry (left to right: discharging, right to left: charging).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The cell's energy is equal to the voltage times the charge.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Each gram of lithium represents Faraday's constant/6.941, or 13,901 coulombs.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] At 3 V, this gives 41.7 kJ per gram of lithium, or 11.6 kWh per kilogram of lithium.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This is slightly more than the heat of combustion of gasoline; however, lithium-ion batteries as a whole are still significantly heavier per unit of energy due to the additional materials used in production.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Note that the cell voltages involved in these reactions are larger than the potential at which an aqueous solutions would electrolyze.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During discharge, lithium ions (Li+ ) carry the current within the battery cell from the negative to the positive electrode, through the non-aqueous electrolyte and separator diaphragm.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During charging, an external electrical power source applies an over-voltage (a voltage greater than the cell's own voltage) to the cell, forcing electrons to flow from the positive to the negative electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The lithium ions also migrate (through the electrolyte) from the positive to the negative electrode where they become embedded in the porous electrode material in a process known as intercalation.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Constant current constant voltage (CC/CV) is the standard method used to charge lithium-ion cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During the constant current phase, the charger applies a constant current to the battery at a steadily increasing voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Once the maximum charging voltage is reached, the charger changes to the constant voltage phase, where the voltage is held steady and the current gradually decreases, until a minimum current threshold is reached.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] If the starting voltage of the cell voltage is too low, a very low charging current is usually used until the voltage reaches a safe level.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This is sometimes referred to as trickle charging.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] When charging lithium-ion batteries made of multiple cells in series, top-balancing is also often performed.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Failure to follow current and voltage limitations can result in excessive coulombic heating of the battery, and in the case of overcharge to voltages higher than designed can lead to an explosion.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Charging temperature limits for Li-ion are stricter than the operating limits.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion chemistry performs well at elevated temperatures but prolonged exposure to heat reduces battery life.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li‑ion batteries offer good charging performance at cooler temperatures and may even allow "fast-charging" within a temperature range of 5 to 45 °C (41 to 113 °F).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Charging should be performed within this temperature range.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] At temperatures from 0 to 5 °C charging is possible, but the charge current should be reduced.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During a low-temperature (under 0 °C) charge, the slight temperature rise above ambient due to the internal cell resistance is beneficial.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] High temperatures during charging may lead to battery degradation and charging at temperatures above 45 °C will degrade battery performance, whereas at lower temperatures the internal resistance of the battery may increase, resulting in slower charging and thus longer charging times.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries gradually self-discharge even if not connected and delivering current.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Li-ion rechargeable batteries have a self-discharge rate typically stated by manufacturers to be 1.5–2% per month.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The rate increases with temperature and state of charge.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A 2004 study found that for most cycling conditions self-discharge was primarily time-dependent; however, after several months of stand on open circuit or float charge, state-of-charge dependent losses became significant.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The self-discharge rate did not increase monotonically with state-of-charge, but dropped somewhat at intermediate states of charge.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Self-discharge rates may increase as batteries age.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By 2007, monthly self-discharge rate was estimated at 2% to 3%, and 2–3% by 2016.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By comparison, the self-discharge rate for NiMH batteries dropped, as of 2017, from up to 30% per month for previously common cells to about 0.08–0.33% per month for low self-discharge NiMH batteries, and is about 10% per month in NiCd batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries may have multiple levels of structure.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Small batteries consist of a single battery cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Larger batteries connect cells in parallel into a module and connect modules in series and parallel into a pack.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Multiple packs may be connected in series to increase the voltage.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries may be equipped with temperature sensors, heating/cooling systems, voltage regulator circuits, voltage taps, and charge-state monitors.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] These components address safety risks like overheating and short circuiting.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] On the macrostructral level (length scale 0.1–5 mm) almost all commercial lithium-ion batteries comprise foil current collectors (aluminium for cathode and copper for anode).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Copper is selected for the anode, because lithium does not alloy with it.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Aluminum is used for the cathode, because it passivates in LiPF6 electrolytes.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Cells with a cylindrical shape are made in a characteristic "swiss roll" manner (known as a "jelly roll" in the US), which means it is a single long "sandwich" of the positive electrode, separator, negative electrode, and separator rolled into a single spool.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One advantage of cylindrical cells is faster production speed.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One disadvantage can be a large radial temperature gradient at high discharge rates.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The absence of a case gives pouch cells the highest gravimetric energy density; however, many applications require containment to prevent expansion when their state of charge (SOC) level is high, and for general structural stability.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Both rigid plastic and pouch-style cells are sometimes referred to as prismatic cells due to their rectangular shapes.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Three basic battery types are used in 2020s-era electric vehicles: cylindrical cells (e.g., Tesla), prismatic pouch (e.g., from LG), and prismatic can cells (e.g., from LG, Samsung, Panasonic, and others).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion flow batteries have been demonstrated that suspend the cathode or anode material in an aqueous or organic solution.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] As of 2014, the smallest Li-ion cell was pin-shaped with a diameter of 3.5 mm and a weight of 0.6 g, made by Panasonic.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A coin cell form factor is available for LiCoO2 cells, usually designated with a "LiR" prefix.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The average voltage of LCO (lithium cobalt oxide) chemistry is 3.6 V if made with hard carbon anode and 3.7 V if made with graphite anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Comparatively, the latter has a flatter discharge voltage curve.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries are used in a multitude of applications, including consumer electronics, toys, power tools, electric vehicles and backup power in telecommunications applications.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries are also used for grid energy storage.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Some submarines have also been equipped with lithium-ion batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Because lithium-ion batteries can have a variety of positive and negative electrode materials, the energy density and voltage vary accordingly.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The open-circuit voltage is higher than in aqueous batteries (such as lead–acid, nickel–metal hydride and nickel–cadmium).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Internal resistance increases with both cycling and age, although this depends strongly on the voltage and temperature the batteries are stored at.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Rising internal resistance causes the voltage at the terminals to drop under load, which reduces the maximum current draw.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Eventually, increasing resistance will leave the battery in a state such that it can no longer support the normal discharge currents requested of it without unacceptable voltage drop or overheating.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries with a lithium iron phosphate positive and graphite negative electrodes have a nominal open-circuit voltage of 3.2 V and a typical charging voltage of 3.6 V.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium nickel manganese cobalt (NMC) oxide positives with graphite negatives have a 3.7 V nominal voltage with a 4.2 V maximum while charging.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The charging procedure is performed at constant voltage with current-limiting circuitry (i.e., charging with constant current until a voltage of 4.2 V is reached in the cell and continuing with a constant voltage applied until the current drops close to zero).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Typically, the charge is terminated at 3% of the initial charge current.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In the past, lithium-ion batteries could not be fast-charged and needed at least two hours to fully charge.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Current-generation cells can be fully charged in 45 minutes or less.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In 2015 researchers demonstrated a small 600 mAh capacity battery charged to 68 percent capacity in two minutes and a 3,000 mAh battery charged to 48 percent capacity in five minutes.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The latter battery has an energy density of 620 W·h/L.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The device employed heteroatoms bonded to graphite molecules in the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Performance of manufactured batteries has improved over time.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] For example, from 1991 to 2005 the energy capacity per price of lithium-ion batteries improved more than ten-fold, from 0.3 W·h per dollar to over 3 W·h per dollar.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In the period from 2011 to 2017, progress has averaged 7.5% annually.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Overall, between 1991 and 2024, prices for all types of lithium-ion cells (in dollars per kWh) fell approximately 99%.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] From 1991 to 2018, energy density more than tripled.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Efforts to increase energy density contributed significantly to cost reduction.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Energy density can also be increased by improvements in the chemistry of the cell, for instance, by full or partial replacement of graphite with silicon.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Silicon anodes enhanced with graphene nanotubes to eliminate the premature degradation of silicon allow for record-breaking battery energy density of up to 350 Wh/kg and lowering EV prices to be competitive with ICEs.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Differently sized cells of the same format (shape) with the same chemistry may have different energy densities.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Jelly roll cells usually have a higher energy density than coin or prismatic cells of the same Ah, because of a tighter/compresses packing of the cell layers.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Among cylindrical cells, those with a larger size have a larger energy density, albeit the exact value strongly depends on the thickness of the electrode layers.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The disadvantage of large cells is decrease of the heat transfer from the cell to its surroundings.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The table below shows the result of an experimental evaluation of a "high-energy" type 3.0 Ah 18650 NMC cell in 2021, round-trip efficiency which compared the energy going into the cell and energy extracted from the cell from 100% (4.2v) SoC to 0% SoC (cut off 2.0v).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A round-trip efficiency is the percent of energy that can be used relative to the energy that went into charging the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The lifespan of a lithium-ion battery is typically defined as the number of full charge-discharge cycles to reach a failure threshold in terms of capacity loss or impedance rise.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Manufacturers' datasheets typically uses the word "cycle life" to specify lifespan in terms of the number of cycles to reach 80% of the rated battery capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Simply storing lithium-ion batteries in the charged state also reduces their capacity (the amount of cyclable Li+) and increases the cell resistance (primarily due to the continuous growth of the solid electrolyte interface on the anode).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Calendar life is used to represent the whole life cycle of battery involving both the cycle and inactive storage operations.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Battery cycle life is affected by many different stress factors including temperature, discharge current, charge current, and state of charge ranges (depth of discharge).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Batteries are not fully charged and discharged in real applications such as smartphones, laptops and electric cars and hence defining battery life via full discharge cycles can be misleading.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] To avoid this confusion, researchers sometimes use cumulative discharge defined as the total amount of charge (Ah) delivered by the battery during its entire life or equivalent full cycles, which represents the summation of the partial cycles as fractions of a full charge-discharge cycle.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Battery degradation during storage is affected by temperature and battery state of charge (SOC) and a combination of full charge (100% SOC) and high temperature (usually > 50 °C) can result in a sharp capacity drop and gas generation.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Multiplying the battery cumulative discharge by the rated nominal voltage gives the total energy delivered over the life of the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] From this one can calculate the cost per kWh of the energy (including the cost of charging).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Over their lifespan, batteries degrade gradually leading to reduced cyclable charge (a.k.a.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Ah capacity) and increased resistance (the latter translates into a lower operating cell voltage).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Also, battery life in room temperature is maximal.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] High charge levels also hasten capacity loss.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Frequent charge to > 90% and discharge to < 10% may also hasten capacity loss.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Keeping the li-ion battery status to about 60% to 80% can reduce the capacity loss.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In a study, scientists provided 3D imaging and model analysis to reveal main causes, mechanics, and potential mitigations of the problematic degradation of the batteries over charge cycles.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium metal plating also results in the loss of lithium inventory (cyclable Ah charge), as well as internal short-circuiting and ignition of a battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Once Li plating commences during cycling, it results in larger slopes of capacity loss per cycle and resistance increase per cycle.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This degradation mechanism become more prominent during fast charging and low temperatures.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Loss of the (negative or positive) electroactive materials due to dissolution (e.g. of Mn3+ species), cracking, exfoliation, detachment or even simple regular volume change during cycling.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] It shows up as both charge and power fade (increased resistance).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Both positive and negative electrode materials are subject to fracturing due to the volumetric strain of repeated (de)lithiation cycles.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Structural degradation of cathode materials, such as Li+/Ni2+ cation mixing in nickel-rich materials.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This manifests as "electrode saturation", loss of cyclable Ah charge and as a "voltage fade".
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Negative copper current collector is particularly prone to corrosion/dissolution at low cell voltages.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] PVDF binder also degrades, causing the detachment of the electroactive materials, and the loss of cyclable Ah charge.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] These are shown in the figure on the right.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] A change from one main degradation mechanism to another appears as a knee (slope change) in the capacity vs. cycle number plot.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Most studies of lithium-ion battery aging have been done at elevated (50–60 °C) temperatures for accelerated aging.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Under these storage conditions, fully charged nickel-cobalt-aluminum and lithium-iron phosphate cells lose ca.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] 20% of their cyclable charge in 1–2 years.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] It is believed that the aforementioned anode aging is the most important degradation pathway in these cases.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] On the other hand, manganese-based cathodes show a (ca.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] 20–50%) faster degradation under these conditions, probably due to the additional mechanism of Mn ion dissolution.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] At 25 °C the degradation of lithium-ion batteries seems to follow the same pathway(s) as the degradation at 50 °C, but with half the speed.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In other words, based on the limited extrapolated experimental data, lithium-ion batteries are expected to lose irreversibly around 20% of their cyclable charge in 3–5 years or 1000–2000 cycles at 25 °C.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium-ion batteries with titanate anodes do not suffer from SEI growth, and last longer (>5000 cycles) than graphite anodes.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] However, in complete cells other degradation mechanisms (i.e. the dissolution of Mn3+ and the Ni2+/Li+ place exchange, decomposition of PVDF binder and particle detachment) show up after 1000–2000 days, and the use titanate anode does not improve full cell durability in practice.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Lithium plating is a phenomenon in which certain conditions lead to metallic lithium forming and depositing onto the surface of the battery's anode rather than intercalating within the anode material's structure.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Low temperatures, overcharging and high charging rates can exacerbate this occurrence.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] During these conditions, lithium ions may not intercalate uniformly into the anode material and form layers of lithium ion on the surface in the form of dendrites.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] **Lithium dendrites** are tiny needle-like structures that can accumulate and pierce the separator, causing a short circuit can initiate thermal runaway.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] This cascade of rapid and uncontrolled energy can lead to battery swelling, increased heat, fires and or explosions.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Additionally, this dendritic growth can lead to side reactions with the electrolyte and convert the fresh plated lithium into electrochemically inert dead lithium.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Moreover, the dendritic growth brought on by lithium plating can degrade the lithium-ion battery and lead to poor cycling efficiency and safety hazards.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Some ways to mitigate lithium plating and the dendritic growth is by controlling the temperature, optimizing the charging conditions, and improving the materials used.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In terms of temperature, the ideal charging temperature is anywhere between 0 °C to 45 °C, but also room temperature is ideal (20 °C to 25 °C).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Advancements in materials innovation requires much research and development in the electrolyte selection and improving the anode resistance to plating.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] One such materials innovation would be to add other compounds to the electrolyte like fluoroethylene carbonate (FEC) to form a rich LiF SEI.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Another novel method would be to coat the separator in a protective shield that essentially "kills" the lithium ions before it can form these dendrites.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Certain manganese containing cathodes can degrade by the Hunter degradation mechanism resulting in manganese dissolution and reduction on the anode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] By the Hunter mechanism for LiMn 2O 4, hydrofluoric acid catalyzes the loss of manganese through disproportionation of a surface trivalent manganese to form a tetravalent manganese and a soluble divalent manganese: 2Mn3+ → Mn2++ Mn4+ Material loss of the spinel results in capacity fade.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Temperatures as low as 50 °C initiate Mn2+ deposition on the anode as metallic manganese with the same effects as lithium and copper plating.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Cycling over the theoretical max and min voltage plateaus destroys the crystal lattice via Jahn-Teller distortion, which occurs when Mn4+ is reduced to Mn3+ during discharge.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Storage of a battery charged to greater than 3.6 V initiates electrolyte oxidation by the cathode and induces SEI layer formation on the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] As with the anode, excessive SEI formation forms an insulator resulting in capacity fade and uneven current distribution.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Storage at less than 2 V results in the slow degradation of LiCoO 2 and LiMn 2O 4 cathodes, the release of oxygen and irreversible capacity loss.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] Discharging below 2 V can also result in the dissolution of the copper anode current collector and, thus, in catastrophic internal short-circuiting on recharge.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] The IEEE standard 1188–1996 recommends replacing lithium-ion batteries in an electric vehicle, when their charge capacity drops to 80% of the nominal value.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] In what follows, we shall use the 20% capacity loss as a comparison point between different studies.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p01] We shall note, nevertheless, that the linear model of degradation (the constant % of charge loss per cycle or per calendar time) is not always applicable, and that a "knee point", observed as a change of the slope, and related to the change of the main degradation mechanism, is often observed.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The problem of lithium-ion battery safety was recognized even before were first commercially released in 1991.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The two main reasons for lithium-ion battery fires and explosions are related to processes on the negative electrode (anode when discharging, cathode when charging).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] During a normal battery charge lithium ions intercalate into graphite.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, if the charge is too fast or the temperature is too low lithium metal starts plating on the negative electrode, and the resulting dendrites can penetrate the battery separator, internally short-circuit the cell, and result in high electric current, heating and ignition.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In other mechanisms, an explosive reaction between the negative electrode material (LiC6) and the solvent (liquid organic carbonate) occurs even at open circuit, provided that the electrode temperature exceeds a certain threshold above 70 °C.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion batteries in the 18650 format or larger may incorporate safety mechanisms such as a current interrupt device (CID) and a positive temperature coefficient (PTC) device.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The CID consists of two metal disks in electrical contact.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] When internal pressure increases, the disks separate, breaking the circuit and terminating the current.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The PTC device is composed of a conductive polymer; an increase in current causes the polymer to heat, increasing its electrical resistance and reducing the current flow.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion batteries can be a safety hazard since they contain a flammable electrolyte and may become pressurized if they become damaged.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] A battery cell charged too quickly could cause a short circuit, leading to overheating, explosions, and fires.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] 4. internal short circuit, e.g. due to manufacturing flaws or aging.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Because of these risks, testing standards are more stringent than those for acid-electrolyte batteries, requiring both a broader range of test conditions and additional battery-specific tests, and there are shipping limitations imposed by safety regulators.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] There have been battery-related recalls by some companies, including the 2016 Samsung Galaxy Note 7 recall for battery fires.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion batteries have a flammable liquid electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] A faulty battery can cause a serious fire.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Faulty chargers can affect the safety of the battery because they can destroy the battery's protection circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] While charging at temperatures below 0 °C, the negative electrode of the cells gets plated with pure lithium, which can compromise the safety of the whole pack.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Short-circuiting a battery will cause the cell to overheat and possibly to catch fire.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Smoke from thermal runaway in a Li-ion battery is both flammable and toxic.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Batteries are tested according to the UL 9540A fire standard, and the TS-800 standard also tests fire propagation from one battery container to adjacent containers.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] UPS Airlines Flight 6 crashed in Dubai after its payload of batteries spontaneously ignited.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] To reduce fire hazards, research projects are intended to develop non-flammable electrolytes.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] If a lithium-ion battery is damaged, crushed, or subjected to a higher electrical load without having overcharge protection, problems may arise.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] External short circuit can trigger a battery explosion.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Such incidents can occur when lithium-ion batteries are not disposed of through the appropriate channels, but are thrown away with other waste.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The way they are treated by recycling companies can damage them and cause fires, which in turn can lead to large-scale conflagrations.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Twelve such fires were recorded in Swiss recycling facilities in 2023.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] If overheated or overcharged, Li-ion batteries may suffer thermal runaway and cell rupture.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] During thermal runaway, internal degradation and oxidization processes can keep cell temperatures above 500 °C, with the possibility of igniting secondary combustibles, as well as leading to leakage, explosion or fire in extreme cases.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] To reduce these risks, many lithium-ion cells (and battery packs) contain fail-safe circuitry that disconnects the battery when its voltage is outside the safe range of 3–4.2 V per cell, or when overcharged or discharged.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium battery packs, whether constructed by a vendor or the end-user, without effective battery management circuits are susceptible to these issues.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Poorly designed or implemented battery management circuits also may cause problems; it is difficult to be certain that any particular battery management circuitry is properly implemented.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium-ion cells are susceptible to stress by voltage ranges outside of safe ones between 2.5 and 3.65/4.1/4.2 or 4.35 V (depending on the components of the cell).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Exceeding this voltage range results in premature aging and in safety risks due to the reactive components in the cells.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] When stored for long periods the small current draw of the protection circuitry may drain the battery below its shutoff voltage; normal chargers may then be useless since the battery management system (BMS) may retain a record of this battery (or charger) "failure".
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Many types of lithium-ion cells cannot be charged safely below 0 °C, as this can result in plating of lithium on the anode of the cell, which may cause complications such as internal short-circuit paths.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] These features are required because the negative electrode produces heat during use, while the positive electrode may produce oxygen.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, these additional devices occupy space inside the cells, add points of failure, and may irreversibly disable the cell when activated.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Further, these features increase costs compared to nickel metal hydride batteries, which require only a hydrogen/oxygen recombination device and a back-up pressure valve.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Contaminants inside the cells can defeat these safety devices.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Also, these features can not be applied to all kinds of cells, e.g., prismatic high-current cells cannot be equipped with a vent or thermal interrupt.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] High-current cells must not produce excessive heat or oxygen, lest there be a failure, possibly violent.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Instead, they must be equipped with internal thermal fuses which act before the anode and cathode reach their thermal limits.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Replacing the lithium cobalt oxide positive electrode material with a lithium metal phosphate such as lithium iron phosphate (LFP) improves cycle counts, shelf life and safety, but lowers capacity.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As of 2006, these safer lithium-ion batteries were mainly used in electric cars and other large-capacity battery applications, where safety is critical.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2016, an LFP-based energy storage system was chosen to be installed in Paiyun Lodge on Mt.Jade (Yushan) (the highest lodge in Taiwan).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As of June 2024, the system was still operating safely.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2006, approximately 10 million Sony batteries used in laptops were recalled, including those in laptops from Dell, Sony, Apple, Lenovo, Panasonic, Toshiba, Hitachi, Fujitsu and Sharp.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The batteries were found to be susceptible to internal contamination by metal particles during manufacture.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Under some circumstances, these particles could pierce the separator, causing a dangerous short circuit.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] IATA estimates that over a billion lithium metal and lithium-ion cells are flown each year.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Some kinds of lithium batteries may be prohibited aboard aircraft because of the fire hazard.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Some postal administrations restrict air shipping (including EMS) of lithium and lithium-ion batteries, either separately or installed in equipment.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2023, most commercial Li-ion batteries employed alkylcarbonate solvents to assure the formation solid electrolyte interface on the negative electrode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Since such solvents are readily flammable, there has been active research to replace them with non-flammable solvents or to add fire suppressants.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Another source of hazard is hexafluorophosphate anion, which is needed to passivate the negative current collector made of aluminium.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Hexafluorophosphate reacts with water and releases volatile and toxic hydrogen fluoride.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Several strategies have been explored for developing non-flammable Li-ion battery electrolytes.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] One approach uses fluorinated (co-)solvents, such as methyl-(2,2,2-trifluoroethyl)-carbonate (FEMC) or methyl-3,3,3-trifluoropropionate (MTFP).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Another approach uses fluorinated anions, such as lithium bis(trifluoromethanesulfonyl)imide or lithium difluoro(oxalato)borate in high concentrations.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As of 2021, almost 90% of raw lithium extraction originated from three countries: Australia (53%), Chile (24%), and China (10%), with almost all production coming from China (56%), Chile (32%) and Argentina (11%).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Extraction of lithium, nickel, and cobalt, manufacture of solvents, and mining byproducts present significant environmental and health hazards.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium extraction can be fatal to aquatic life due to water pollution.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It is known to cause surface water contamination, drinking water contamination, respiratory problems, ecosystem degradation and landscape damage.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It also leads to unsustainable water consumption in arid regions (1.9 million liters per ton of lithium).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Massive byproduct generation of lithium extraction also presents unsolved problems, such as large amounts of magnesium and lime waste.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lithium mining takes place in North and South America, Asia, South Africa, Australia, and China.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cobalt for Li-ion batteries is largely mined in the Congo (see also Mining industry of the Democratic Republic of the Congo).
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Open-pit cobalt mining has led to deforestation and habitat destruction in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Open-pit nickel mining has led to environmental degradation and pollution in developing countries such as the Philippines and Indonesia.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In 2024, nickel mining and processing was one of the main causes of deforestation in Indonesia.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Manufacturing a kg of Li-ion battery takes about 67 megajoules (MJ) of energy.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The global warming potential of lithium-ion batteries manufacturing strongly depends on the energy source used in mining and manufacturing operations, and is difficult to estimate, but one 2019 study estimated 73 kg CO2e/kWh.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Effective recycling can reduce the carbon footprint of the production significantly.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The Li-ion battery recycling rate is often misconstrued to be 5%, in reality, insufficient research exists to determine the exact figure.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The European Union estimates 49% of portable batteries sold were collected for recycling in 2023, whilst the UK estimates 45% as of 2026.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] New EU legislation requires 70% of collected Li-ion battery material to be recovered through recycling by 2031, which must include recovery rates of 80% for lithium and 95% for cobalt, nickel, and manganese; however, no recycled lithium has re-entered the EU as of 2023.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] These measures aim to aid sustainability efforts and reduce pressure on raw material extraction, as demand for lithium and cobalt is expected to increase 8-fold by 2040, far exceeding current production capabilities.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Most research focuses on the recovery of active materials, especially lithium which is a critical raw material; however, through advanced recycling techniques and more sustainable design considerations, electrolytes, binders, and separators can also recycled.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Recycling is a multi-step process, starting with the storage of batteries before disposal, followed by manual testing, disassembling, and finally the chemical separation of battery components.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Re-use of the battery is preferred over complete recycling as there is less embodied energy in the process.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] As these batteries are a lot more reactive than classical vehicle waste like tire rubber, there are significant risks to stockpiling used batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The pyrometallurgical method uses a high-temperature furnace to reduce the components of the metal oxides in the battery to an alloy of Co, Cu, Fe, and Ni.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This is the most common and commercially established method of recycling and can be combined with other similar batteries to increase smelting efficiency and improve thermodynamics.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The metal current collectors aid the smelting process, allowing whole cells or modules to be melted at once.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The product of this method is a collection of metallic alloy, slag, and gas.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] At high temperatures, the polymers used to hold the battery cells together burn off and the metal alloy can be separated through a hydrometallurgical process into its separate components.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The slag can be further refined or used in the cement industry.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The process is relatively risk-free and the exothermic reaction from polymer combustion reduces the required input energy.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, in the process, the plastics, electrolytes, and lithium salts will be lost.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This method involves the use of aqueous solutions to remove the desired metals from the cathode.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The most common reagent is sulfuric acid.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Factors that affect the leaching rate include the concentration of the acid, time, temperature, solid-to-liquid-ratio, and reducing agent.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Once leached, the metals can be extracted through precipitation reactions controlled by changing the pH level of the solution.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cobalt, the most expensive metal, can then be recovered in the form of sulfate, oxalate, hydroxide, or carbonate.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] More recently, recycling methods experiment with the direct reproduction of the cathode from the leached metals.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In these procedures, concentrations of the various leached metals are premeasured to match the target cathode and then the cathodes are directly synthesized.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The main issues with this method, however, are the large volume of solvent required and the high cost of neutralization.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Although it is easy to shred up the battery, mixing the cathode and anode at the beginning complicates the process, so they will also need to be separated.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Unfortunately, the current design of batteries makes the process extremely complex and it is difficult to separate the metals in a closed-loop battery system.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Shredding and dissolving may occur at different locations.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Direct recycling is the removal of the cathode or anode from the electrode, which are then reconditioned and reused in a new battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Mixed metal-oxides can be added to the new electrode with very little change to the crystal morphology.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The process generally involves the addition of new lithium to replenish the loss of lithium in the cathode due to degradation from cycling.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cathode strips are obtained from the dismantled batteries, then soaked in NMP, and undergo sonication to remove excess deposits.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It is treated hydrothermally with a solution containing LiOH/Li2SO4 before annealing.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This method is extremely cost-effective for noncobalt-based batteries as the raw materials do not make up the bulk of the cost.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Direct recycling avoids the time-consuming and expensive purification steps, which is great for low-cost cathodes such as LiMn2O4 and LiFePO4.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] For these cheaper cathodes, most of the cost, embedded energy, and carbon footprint is associated with the manufacturing rather than the raw material.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] It is experimentally shown that direct recycling can reproduce similar properties to pristine graphite.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The drawback of the method lies in the condition of the retired battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In the case where the battery is relatively healthy, direct recycling can cheaply restore its properties.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, for batteries where the state of charge is low, direct recycling may not be worth the investment.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The process must also be tailored to the specific cathode composition, and therefore the process must be configured to one type of battery at a time.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Lastly, in a time with rapidly developing battery technology, the design of a battery today may no longer be desirable a decade from now, rendering direct recycling ineffective.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Physical materials separation recovered materials by mechanical crushing and exploiting physical properties of different components such as particle size, density, ferromagnetism and hydrophobicity.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Copper, aluminum and steel casing can be recovered by sorting.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The remaining materials, called "black mass", which is composed of nickel, cobalt, lithium and manganese, need a secondary treatment to recover.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] For the biological metals reclamation or bio-leaching, the process uses microorganisms to digest metal oxides selectively.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Then, recyclers can reduce these oxides to produce metal nanoparticles.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Although bio-leaching has been used successfully in the mining industry, this process is still nascent to the recycling industry and plenty of opportunities exists for further investigation.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Electrolyte recycling consists of two phases.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The collection phase extracts the electrolyte from the spent Li-ion battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This can be achieved through mechanical processes, distillation, freezing, solvent extraction, and supercritical fluid extraction.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Due to the volatility, flammability, and sensitivity of the electrolyte, the collection process poses a greater difficulty than the collection process for other components of a Li-ion battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The next phase consists of separation/electrolyte regeneration.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Separation consists of isolating the individual components of the electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This approach is often used for the direct recovery of the Li salts from the organic solvents.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] In contrast, regeneration of the electrolyte aims to preserve the electrolyte composition by removing impurities which can be achieved through filtration methods.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The recycling of the electrolytes, which consists 10–15 wt.% of the Li-ion battery, provides both economic and environmental benefits.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] These benefits include the recovery of the valuable Li-based salts and the prevention of hazardous compounds, such as volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and carcinogens, being released into the environment.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Compared to electrode recycling, less focus is placed on recycling the electrolyte of Li-ion batteries due to lower economic benefits and greater process challenges.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Such challenges can include the difficulty associated with recycling different electrolyte compositions, removing side products accumulated from electrolyte decomposition during its runtime, and removal of electrolyte adsorbed onto the electrodes.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Due to these challenges, current pyrometallurgical methods of Li-ion battery recycling forgo electrolyte recovery, releasing hazardous gases upon heating.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] However, due to high energy consumption and environmental impact, future recycling methods are being directed away from this approach.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Extraction of raw materials for lithium-ion batteries may present dangers to local people, especially land-based indigenous populations.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Cobalt sourced from the Democratic Republic of the Congo is often mined by workers using hand tools with few safety precautions, resulting in frequent injuries and deaths.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Pollution from these mines has exposed people to toxic chemicals that health officials believe to cause birth defects and breathing difficulties.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Human rights activists have alleged, and investigative journalism reported confirmation, that child labor is used in these mines.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Development of the Thacker Pass lithium mine in Nevada, USA has been met with protests and lawsuits from several indigenous tribes who have said they were not provided free prior and informed consent and that the project threatens cultural and sacred sites.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Links between resource extraction and missing and murdered indigenous women have also prompted local communities to express concerns that the project will create risks to indigenous women.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Protestors have been occupying the site of the proposed mine since January, 2021.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Researchers are actively working to improve the power density, safety, cycle durability (battery life), recharge time, cost, flexibility, and other characteristics, as well as research methods and uses, of these batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Solid-state batteries are being researched as a breakthrough in technological barriers.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Currently, solid-state batteries are expected to be the most promising next-generation battery, and various companies are working to popularize them.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Research areas for lithium-ion batteries include extending lifetime, increasing energy density, improving safety, reducing cost, and increasing charging speed, among others.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Research has been under way in the area of non-flammable electrolytes as a pathway to increased safety based on the flammability and volatility of the organic solvents used in the typical electrolyte.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Strategies include aqueous lithium-ion batteries, ceramic solid electrolytes, polymer electrolytes, ionic liquids, and heavily fluorinated systems.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] One of the ways to improve batteries is to combine the various cathode materials.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] This allows researchers to improve on the qualities of a material, while limiting the negatives.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] One possibility is coating lithium nickel manganese oxide with lithium iron phosphate through resonant acoustic mixing.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] The resulting material benefits from an increase electrochemical performance and improved capacity retention.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Similar work was done with iron (III) phosphate.
[src:battery-chemistry/lithium-ion-battery-p02] Advances in anionic redox understanding have led to stabilization strategies like surface fluorination, improving cycling stability and safety.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] In a battery electric vehicle (BEV), the state of charge indicates the remaining energy in the battery pack.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] The state of charge can help to reduce electrical car owners' anxiety when they are waiting in the line or stay at home since it will reflect the progress of charging and let owners know when it will be ready.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] However on any vehicle dashboard, especially in plug-in hybrid vehicles, the state of charge presented as a gauge or percentage value may not be representative of a real level of charge.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] A noticeable amount of energy may be reserved for hybrid-work operations.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] Examples of such cars are Mitsubishi Outlander PHEV (all versions/years of production), where a charge level of zero is indicated to the driver when the real charge level is 20–22%.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] Another one is the BMW i3 REX (Range Extender version), where about 6% of SoC is reserved for PHEV-alike operations.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] State of charge is also known to impact battery aging.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] To extend battery lifetime, extremes of state of charge should be avoided and reduced variations windows are also preferable.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] Usually, SoC cannot be measured directly but it can be estimated from direct measurement variables in two ways: offline and online.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] In offline techniques, the battery desires to be charged and discharged in constant rate such as Coulomb-counting.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] This method gives precise estimation of battery SoC, but they are protracted, costly, and interrupt main battery performance.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] Therefore, researchers are looking for some online techniques.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] This method works only with batteries that offer access to their liquid electrolyte, such as non-sealed lead acid batteries.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] The specific gravity of the electrolyte can be used to indicate the SoC of the battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] Hydrometers are used to calculate the specific gravity of a battery.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] To find specific gravity, it is necessary to measure out volume of the electrolyte and to weigh it.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] Then specific gravity is given by (mass of electrolyte [g]/ volume of electrolyte [ml])/ (Density of Water, i.e.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] To find SoC from specific gravity, a look-up table of SG vs SoC is needed.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] Refractometry has been shown to be a viable method for continuous monitoring of the state of charge.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] The refractive index of the battery electrolyte is directly relatable to the specific gravity or density of the electrolyte of the cell.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] Notably, analysis of electrolyte does not provide information about the state-of-charge in the case of lithium-ion batteries and other batteries, that do not produce or consume solvent or dissolved species during their operation.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] This method converts a reading of the battery voltage to SoC, using the known discharge curve (voltage vs.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] However, the voltage is more significantly affected by the battery current (due to the battery's electrochemical kinetics) and temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] This method can be made more accurate by compensating the voltage reading by a correction term proportional to the battery current, and by using a look-up table of battery's open circuit voltage vs. temperature.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] In fact, it is a stated goal of battery design to provide a voltage as constant as possible no matter the SoC, which makes this method difficult to apply.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] For batteries, that have voltage independent on their state-of-charge (such as lithium iron phosphate battery), open-circuit voltage measurements cannot provide a reliable estimate of the SoC.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] On the other hand, batteries with a sloping voltage-charge curves (such as nickel-cobalt-manganese battery), are more amenable to SoC estimation from the open-circuit voltage measurements.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] This method, also known as *coulomb counting*, calculates the SoC by measuring the battery current and integrating it in time.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] Maxim Integrated touts a combined voltage and charge approach that is claimed superior to either method alone; it is implemented in their ModelGauge m3 series of chips, such as MAX17050, which is used in the Nexus 6 and Nexus 9 Android devices, for example.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] To overcome the shortcomings of the voltage method and the current integration method, a Kalman filter can be used.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] The battery can be described with an electrical model which the Kalman filter will use to predict the over-voltage given the observed current.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] In combination with coulomb counting, it can make an accurate estimation of the state of charge.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] The strength of this technique is that a Kalman filter adjusts its relative trust of the battery voltage and coulomb counting in real time.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] This method can be used with certain NiMH batteries, whose internal pressure increases rapidly when the battery is charged.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] More commonly, a pressure switch indicates if the battery is fully charged.
[src:battery-chemistry/state-of-charge] This method may be improved by taking into account Peukert's law which is a function of charge/discharge current.
